So what’s the take away here? Take your time off, work as much as they’re paying you for and that’s it, talk about your pay openly, know your enemy, demand to be paid what you deserve, realize you deserve more, and question everything you think you know about work.

No one marches up to whoever makes pay decisions and goes, “This, this right here is bullshit.” Because they’re afraid that they’re disposable, that they’ll be tossed aside and replaced. We’ve been taught that, that we’re disposable and we should be thankful to even have a job.

Then we say, “I’ll just work harder! Then I’ll get what I deserve!” but it’s never the truth. My heart breaks for people who put DECADES into a job that only make cents more than someone who just started. And more often than not they see the new, young worker as a threat.

And when you find out that you’re being cheated and taken advantage of, know that your co-workers aren’t your enemy. That’s another safeguard the system has in place. If your co-worker is making more than you society has taught us to be jealous.

Thankful for the crumbs that we get. But don’t tell anyone else much you’re making, because that’s improper. That in of itself is such a bullshit concept. Talk about what you make. Make it known, make it public. I make $17/hour working as a food host at a hospital.

Of course, we cant forget that the sheer capitalist hellscape that is the United States of America straight forces people to work absurd hours, doing back breaking work, just to survive. And we take what were given because we’ve been taught to believe that we should be thankful.

I, like so many others, just straight up did this to ourselves. No one pushed us, no one demanded it… At least not in my case. If you’ll spare me some dramatic imagery we put the shackles on ourselves.

It’s the kind of culture where it’s normal to say “I worked an 18 hour shift at a restaurant where I made $11/hour” (yes it happened, what’s worse is that I did it voluntarily). And that’s what’s possibly the most sickening of all of this.

Part of it is that I grew up in a culture, like many of you that idolizes hustle culture. Where taking all of your pto was “working the system”, where your reward for going above and beyond was usually worthless recognition, a minuscule pay raise or more responsibility,

Now it’s like, for what? Why did I break myself for businesses that ultimately cared nothing for me? Why didn’t I channel that time into something I really gave a damn about? Why didn’t I take time off and work only as much as I was paid to?

I chose work over spending time with friends, with family, with doing things I actually cared about. When I was at work, I put so much of myself into my work at every company. It wasn’t enough for me to just do my job, I had to be the best.

Looking back I’m guilty of straight up bragging about the time I spent working. But now I look back on it and feel repulsed. I started working when I was 15. I chose work over a social life in high school. I had friends but I never went out.

So naturally I took the same kind of stance when it came to work. I was proud of working 14 hour shifts, of not taking days off for huge stretches of time, of not going on vacation. At work I always gave 154%, because that’s just what you did.

For most of my life I wore the time I spent at work with a fierce pride. Even before I could work I was taught by my family that you work and you work your damned hardest from start to finish. I watched both parents do it, I watched both of my brothers do it.

Gonna ramble for a moment:
So over the years my perception of work has changed, especially with in the last year or so. I can’t attribute it to any one thing, it was more a gradual realization than an epiphany.
